definition.value: A ketohexose often involved in the commercial production of vitamin C. It has been found to occur naturally in grapes.
A glycerophosphoglycerol in which sn-glycerol, acylated at O(2), is linked through a phospho group at O(3) to O(1) of glycerol.
A phenylhydrazine that is the monophenyl derivative of hydrazine.
A dichlorophenol with the chloro substituents at positions 2 and 5.
An indanone with an oxo substituent at position 2. It is a metabolite of indane.
A maltotriose trisaccharide in which the glucose residue at the reducing end is in the pyranose ring form and has alpha configuration at the anomeric carbon atom..
A member of the class of glycolaldehydes that is 3,4-dihydroxymandelaldehyde in which the hydroxy group at position 4 is replaced by a methoxy group.
An organonitrogen heterocyclic antibiotic that contains a beta-lactam ring.
A D-galactosyl-N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl-D-galactosyl-D-glucosylceramide containing beta-linkages exclusively.
A monounsaturated long-chain fatty acid composed of tridecanoic acid having a 2-cyclopentenyl substituent at the 13-position.
A harmala alkaloid in which the harman skeleton is hydroxy-substituted at C-7 and has been reduced across the 3,4 bond.
Isoflavone in which the double bond between positions 2 and 3 has been reduced to a single bond.
An optically active form of histidine having D-configuration.
A dTDP-sugar having 3-dimethylamino-3,4,6-trideoxy-alpha-D-glucose (alpha-D-desosamine) as the sugar component.
A member of the class of cinnamaldehydes that is cinnamaldehyde substituted by a hydroxy group at position 4 and methoxy groups at positions 3 and 5.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is 2-oxobutanoic acid which is substituted by a phosphonooxy group at position 4 and a hydroxy group at the 3-pro-R position.
An amino cyclitol consisting of scyllo-inositol with the hydroxy groups at positions 1 and 3 replaced by unsubstituted amino groups.
Dehydroascorbic acid having the L-configuration.
A propanone that is acetone in which one of the methyl hydrogens is replaced by a hydroxy group.
A tropane alkaloid obtained from leaves of the South American shrub Erythroxylon coca.
An L-arginine derivative that is L-arginine in which the terminal nitrogen of the guanidyl group is replaced by a nitro group.
A steroid alkaloid that is con-5-enine substituted by a N,N-dimethylamino group at position 3. It has been isolated from the plant species of the family Apocynaceae.
An omega-carboxyacyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the 1-carboxy group of mesaconic acid.

A rare, non-protein amino acid and end-product of pyrimidine metabolism, excreted in urine and found in some antibiotics of fungal origin. With the exception of a few bacteria, it is non-metabolisable, and therefore used in bioassays.
